<DOC><DOCNO> AP890607-0115 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-06-07-89 1421EST</FILEID><FIRST>r a PM-TankDeath     06-07 0178</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Tank Death,0187</SECOND><HEAD>One Killed in National Guard Tank Collision</HEAD><DATELINE>HELENA, Mont. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Two National Guard M-1 tanks collided atFort Harrison today, killing one driver and seriously injuring theother, officials said.   Sheriff Chuck O'Reilly said one of the 60-ton Abrams battle tanksended up on top of the other, causing severe damage to both.   Authorities said the drivers were National Guard employeesperforming technical checks on the recently arrived $1.8 milliontanks. The accident occurred before 9 a.m. on a flat, open trainingground, O'Reilly said.   The cause was under investigation.   The injured man was hospitalized in Helena, O'Reilly said.   The M-1 has been used by the active Army since 1982. It has afour-person crew and a top speed of 45 mph and fires a 105mm cannon.   The Montana Army National Guard received 120 of the tanks duringthe winter as part of the reorganization of Montana's 163rd ArmoredCavalry Regiment into a brigade, a larger unit with different duties.   Guard units in North Carolina, South Carolina and Georgia alsouse the M-1.</TEXT></DOC>